properties.title: Transnistria
properties.infoTemplate: Transnistria is a self-proclaimed republic located on the eastern bank of the Dniestr river. After the independence of Moldovia in 1992, the Russian speaking population, who predominantly inhabited the area, declared independence from the Moldovian government primarily due to the pro-Moldovian ethnic policies that were implemented. The Transnistrian separatists achieved independence with the help of Russia, the latter still maintains 1500 troops in the area.

properties.title: Crimea
properties.infoTemplate: The Crimean peninsula was annexed by Russia from Ukraine in 2014 following the Euromaidan revolution. Historically, the area, once conquered by Catharina the Great, has been perceived by Russians as an inseparable part of Russia. The Crimea is home of the Russian Black Sea Fleet. Furthermore, due to its geographical position almost in the middle of the Black Sea it is of great strategic importance for the control of that same body of water.

properties.title: Abkhazia
properties.infoTemplate: Abkhazia is a breakaway region in Northern Georgia. The area gained independence after a short war with the Georgian government in 1992-93. Violence once again flared up in 2008 during the August war. Since then, Russia guarantees the de facto independence of Abkhazia through the presence of a large contingent of military troops.

properties.title: South-Ossetia
properties.infoTemplate: South-Ossetia is formally part of Georgia but declared independence in 1991. Since then, it is de facto independent state, but only recognized by a handful of other countries. In august 2008 skirmishes between Georgian forces and Ossetian separatists escalated to a full blown war between Georgia and Russia as the latter came to the assistance of the Ossetians. Since the war, Russia maintains a large military presence in South Ossetia.

properties.title: DPR and LPR
properties.infoTemplate: The Donetsk People's Republic and Luhansk People's Republic, sometime referred to as Novorossiya, are two self-proclaimed states in eastern Ukraine. During the Maidan revolution the two areas revolted against Kiev. In the summer of 2014 the Ukrainian armed forces tried to regain the areas but where defeated by 'little green men'. The latter refers to Russian military forces in unmarked uniforms.
